{{Infobox musical artist | honorific_prefix = | name = Joseph Francis Petrič | honorific_suffix = [[Bachelor of Music|BM]], [[Master of Arts|MA]] | image = JosephPetric.jpg | image_upright = | image_size = | landscape = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank --> | alt = | caption = Joseph Petric during rehearsal (2013) | background = non_vocal_instrumentalist | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = | alias = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|10|08}} | birth_place = [[Guelph, Ontario]], Canada | origin = | death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) --> | death_place = | genre = | occupation = [[Musician]], [[musicologist]], [[teacher]], and [[author]] | instrument = | years_active = 1979–present | label = | associated_acts = | website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} --> | module = | module2 = | module3 = }} '''Joseph Francis Petrič''' (born October 8, 1952) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] concert [[accordionist]], musicologist, teacher, and author.
==Early life and education== He was born in [[Guelph]], [[Ontario]] and raised in [[Acton, Ontario|Acton]],<ref>{{cite news |last= Okum|first= Leanne|date= May 26, 1992|title= Joseph Petric comes home with his Academy Players|url= http://news.haltonhills.halinet.on.ca/106744/page/8|work= Acton Tanner|page=7}}</ref> to a family of the political diaspora that left [[Slovenija]] in 1945. Taken by his father to his first accordion lesson at age five, he studied with local teachers until 1968, when he enrolled at Toronto’s [[Royal Conservatory of Music]]. In 1975 he completed his [[Bachelor of Music]] at [[Queen’s University]], [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]]. That same year, he moved to [[Toronto]] and completed his master's degree in Musicology in 1977. Influenced by the [[Toronto]] visit of Swiss accordionist Hugo Noth in 1975, Petric studied at the [[:de:Hochschule für Musik Trossingen|Hochschule für Musik]] in [[Trossingen]] in 1977.<ref>{{cite book |last= Gervasoni|first= Pierre|date= 1986|title= L’Accordéon : Instrument du XXe siécle|trans-title= The Accordion: Instrument of the 20th Century|page= 72|language= French|location= Paris|publisher= Éditions Mazo|isbn=2-95015070-5|oclc=869159905}}</ref>
==Musical career== In October 1979, Petric made his Canadian debut with Toronto’s Arraymusic Ensemble, and became the first accordionist to win the CBC National Radio Auditions, which launched his career on both the English and French radio services of Canada.<ref>{{cite book |last= Macerollo|first= Joseph|date= 1980|title= Accordion Resource Manual|url= |location= Willowdale|publisher= Avondale Press|page= 20|isbn= 0-9690452-8-X|ol= 3911334M}}</ref> He started his international career in [[Washington, D.C.]] at the [[Kennedy Centre]] in 1986 and in [[London]] at [[St John's, Smith Square]] in 1992.
Throughout the 1980s, his artistic activity included commissioning, performing and recording,<ref>{{cite journal |last= Gervasoni|first= Pierre|date= 1988|title= Un Instrument insolite de l’avant-garde canadienne : L’Accordéon|trans-title= The Accordion: Insolent instrument of the Canadian avant-garde|url= |language= French|journal= Boréales : Revue du Centre de recherches inter-nordiques|publisher= Centre de recherches inter-nordiques|location= [[Suresnes]]|volume= |issue= 36-37|pages= 93–97|issn= 0395-3998}}</ref> with invitations from [[Serge Garant]] and [[SMCQ|Montreal’s SMCQ ensemble]], ACREQ, the string quartets [[Alcan]] and [[St. Germain (musician)|St. Germain]], [[Le Nouvel Ensemble Moderne|the NEM Ensemble]], and Pentaèdre; he received invitations to the McGill, [[Domaine Forget]], and Bic St. Fabien festivals. He was the artistic director of The Big Squeeze accordion festival in [[Toronto]] in 1991, as well as the Virtuosi Series for the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] at the Glenn Gould Hall in 1993. In 1998, he turned his attention to the research of period performance practices and instrument building, with the assistance of a [[Canada Council|Canada Council Senior Artist’s Grant]], working with period keyboard artists [[Colin Tilney]] and [[Boyd McDonald]]<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.thewholenote.com/index.php/booksrecords2/booksrecords2-2/12929-a-victorian-romance-music-for-the-english-concertina-joseph-petric-boyd-mcdonald|title=A Victorian Romance - Music for the English Concertina - Joseph Petric; Boyd McDonald|last=Kiik|first=Tiina|journal=The Whole Note|volume= 17|issue= 2|page= 63|date=October 2011}}</ref>
In 2000, he became the artistic director for the Carte Blanche Series in Montreal for the [[Radio Canada|Société Radio Canada]], and [[Quebec City]] in 2003.
His postmodern approaches attracted the marketing support of four international management companies: MGAM in [[Toronto]], NCCP in [[London]], Sarah Turner Communications in [[Paris]], and Columbia Artists in [[New York City]]; as well as financial support of the Koussevitsky Foundation, CBC, and the Canada Council for the Arts. He enjoyed special relationships with Bob Aitken’s New Music Concerts in Toronto, the [[SMCQ|Societe Contemporaine de Quebec]] in [[Montreal]], the [[Canadian Electronic Ensemble]], and composer [[Witold Lutoslawski]].<ref>{{cite thesis|last=Pigula|first=Szymon|title=Rola akordeonu i jego znaczenie we współczesnej literaturze kameralnej na podstawie wybranych przykładów|date=2011|degree=|publisher=[[Karol Szymanowski Academy of Music]], [[Katowice]]|url=|doi=|language=Polish|trans-title=The role of the accordion and its importance in contemporary chamber music literature, based on selected examples|type=|chapter=|docket=|oclc=978205013|pages=12-32}}</ref> A steady stream of international tours followed, with up to 80 concerts a year, and international recordings for [[CBC Radio|CBC]], [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|SRC]], [[BBC Radio 3]], and [[PBS radio|PBS]] (USA). His numerous collaborations include: the Petric-Forget Duo, Pentaèdre, Canada’s Penderecki Quartet, Duo Contempera, the Trio Diomira, [[Pauline Oliveros]], and the ensembles Erosonic and Bellows and Brass.
Other notable performances include: premiere performance and recording of [[Peter Paul Koprowski]]'s Accordion Concerto with the [[Toronto Symphony Orchestra]] (1996); ''[[Sequenza|Berio Sequenza]]'' at [[Tanglewood Music Center|Tanglewood’s Seiji Ozawa Hall]], with members of the [[Boston Symphony Orchestra]] (2000); the sock puppet opera, ''The Perfect Cake'', by [[Alain Trudel]]; [[Linda Bouchard]]'s multi-disciplinary work ''Murderous Little World'' with Bellows and Brass; the [[:de:Schubertiade Vorarlberg|Hohenems Schubertiade]] with tenor [[Christoph Pregardien]], and the Montreal's Pentaèdre in Normand Forget's chamber version of ''[[Winterreise|Die Winterreise]]''(2009); the [[Israeli Opera|Israeli Opera Tel Aviv]] (2011), and the [[Berlin Philharmonic|Berlin Philharmonic Series]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/466690113377624/|title=KAMMERMUSIK: CHRISTOPH PRÉGARDIEN, Tenor CHRISTINE SCHÄFER, Sopran|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-02}}</ref> (2013).
By 2010 his postmodern discography numbered 32 CD titles. In 2013 he co-directed the first Canadian performance of the complete ''Berio Sequenze'' for the University of Toronto New Music Festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musiccentre.ca/about/ambassadors|title=CMC 50th Anniversary Ambassadors|website=musiccentre.ca|publisher=[[Canadian Music Centre]]|access-date=2017-03-02}}</ref> He was honored by the Canadian recording industry with a JUNO nomination for Best Composition in 2003; Quebec’s Prix Opus for Best Concert in 2009; and a Prix Opus in 2011, for Best Recording.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/joseph-petric-emc/|title=Joseph Petric|last=Verdejo|first=Adrian|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia|access-date=2017-03-02|language=en}}</ref> He was awarded the designation "Friend of Canadian Music" by the [[Canadian Music Centre]] in 2005, and the designation "Ambassador of Canadian Music" in a public ceremony at Ottawa’s [[National Arts Centre]] in 2009. In 2013, the [[International Music Council|IMC]], [[UNESCO]] and the Conféderation International des Accordeonistes presented Petric with the Award of Merit, for outstanding lifetime contributions to the accordion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.accordions.com/cia/cia_merit.htm|title=CIA Merit Awards|website=www.accordions.com|publisher=Confédération Internationale des Accordéonistes CIA|access-date=2017-03-02}}</ref>
